Not working these last couple weeks is number one.

>I plan out large blocks of time to write.
>I think about the characters, conversations, and the world when not writing.
>I have a skeleton of what I want to write when I sit down.
>knowing the characters really helps to add details and humor as I go.
>10-12 hours later with appropriate breaks I have 2-3k words down.

I never thought I would be able to get that much done when I first started writing but it's what works for me now. The last two updates I did came from two days of writing each with one or two days off in between. They were like 95% done when I finished them, with a few trouble paragraphs needing clarification, breaking up, or moving around. "days off" usually include reviewing what I wrote the day before to think about it or make minor edits.

I trust writers block more than I used to, and I skip to write something else. If I'm struggling on a scene it's usually because I haven't thought about it enough, and made too many assumptions about how simple it would be. I try to just put words down when I'm writing, the thinking should take place elsewhere. I know that probably sounds weird, but again its what works for me.

This story also is going easier for me than others because I spent a while with the writing prompt and doing the world building beforehand. Just as a back burner idea while I did other stuff. So I sort of had a running start.

Rabbits, rats, and such- basements and bunkers galore, buildings are mostly above ground only when necessary
Foxes- more normal houses, but they're almost always built into the sides of hills so the basements can have windows
Otters- those tropical villages that are in water either by pillars down into the seabed or just outright floating
Beavers- like a mix between otters and foxes except you can't go ten feet without running into the Hoover Dam for the nth time
Lions- like a mix between the estates of wealthy Romans and the classical 50's America, very large courtyards with even larger lawns
Horses- n/a, nomads
Bears- large wooden cottages built somewhat similarly to foxes' except very stocky and no basement windows
Deer- very numerous small, simple, wooden cottages
Wolves- n/a, nomads
Cows- basically just India
Tigers- pagodas and Dzong
Raccoons- completely serious treehouse use wherever possible

Anonymous Sun 07 Jun 2020 19:36:18 No.30762644 Report
Quoted By:
>>30760031
That depends.
Since my anthros dispersed over Earth like the humans there's not one monolithic culture. On the other hand, I wanted the parts set in modern times to be recognizable to readers.

Historically, agriculture started for different reasons in each. I saw canid types as extending the natural pack to an extended family structure. As they lived longer, it became important to have a home base to shelter the old rather than constantly be on the move.
Since keeping a small village healthy requires some exchange of people with neighboring areas, trade between distant relatives built networks managed by the venerable elders.

In modern times their houses tend to be large if Grandma or Grandpa lives with two or three of his adult children and their families.
The rich and eccentric might model the interiors top reflect classical designs of carved wood and stone.
The single and loners might find solace in a more cosmopolitan existence.
